	year = {2025},
	journal = {Energy},
	volume = {338},
	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1016/j.energy.2025.138670},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105018305178&doi=10.1016%2Fj.energy.2025.138670&partnerID=40&md5=1056edf24b0f3982be42263a085a7544},
	affiliations = {State Key Laboratory of Multiphase Flow in Power Engineering, Xi'an, Shaanxi, China},
	abstract = {Supercritical water gasification (SCWG) is a promising process for treating oily wastewater (OW). Here, an auto-thermal system that simultaneously generates hydrogen, electricity and heat was developed based on the SCWG of OW and the impact of operational parameters on product distribution, system efficiency and environmental effect was analyzed. The results showed that the hydrogen production was significantly affected by the water to oil ratio (W/O) and the SCWG temperature. The reaction system presented the excess energy state when the W/O was less than 9 and the deficient energy state when it was greater than 10. Adjusting the SCWG temperature and the gas flow entering combustion furnace could effectively regulate the self-heat coupling state of the reaction system, thereby improving the system efficiency. When the W/O reached 9, the reaction system attained a comparatively ideal self-heat coupling state, and the energy efficiency and exergy efficiency of the system were 71.66 % and 30.01 %, respectively. The reactor and the heat exchanger were the key units causing exergy losses, accounting for 52.12 % and 33.75 % of the total exergy losses, respectively. The optimal GWP value with carbon capture and storage (CCS) is 0.65 kg CO<inf>2</inf>-eq, which was 29.35 % less than without CCS. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
