	abstract = {This research presents a comprehensive energy, exergy, economics, and enviro-economic of macro-encapsulated phase change material (PHCM)-integrated single basin solar still for wastewater treatment. The study investigates the system's performance at three different wastewater depths (40 %, 50 %, and 60 %) with varying masses of stearic acid as PHCM and compares the results with a conventional solar still. The novelty of this work lies in integrating macro-encapsulated PHCM, which significantly enhances thermal energy storage improving system energy & exergy efficiencies and productivity. The results demonstrated that energy and exergy efficiency is increased in the range of almost 28–99 % and 21 %-129 % respectively compared to traditional solar still. The total output productivity at 40 % depth for Test 1–4 was found to be 2500, 1850, 1620, and 1172 ml m<sup>-2</sup>d<sup>-1</sup> respectively. Similarly, at 50 % depth, the total output productivity was 2028, 1625, 1439 & 970 ml m<sup>-2</sup>d<sup>-1</sup> for Test 5–8 respectively. For 60 % depth, the total output productivity for Test 9–12 was 2040, 1550, 1410, and 935 ml m<sup>-2</sup>d<sup>-1</sup> respectively. The average value of levelized energy cost (LEC), net present value (NTPV), and payback period (PYP) of the solar still unit with and without macro-encapsulated PHCM is found to be 3.36 INR/kWh or 0.040 USD/kWh, 35,030 INR, & 4.46 years and 5.08 INR/kWh, 25,559 INR, & 9.76 years respectively. Furthermore, the system with and without macro-encapsulated PHCM mitigates approximately 8–23 and 8–11 tCO<inf>2</inf>/lifetime respectively. This study provides a novel approach to improving solar still efficiency through macro-encapsulated PHCM, offering a cost-effective and sustainable solution for wastewater treatment. © 2025 Elsevier B.V.},
