	url = {https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105011211377&doi=10.1016%2Fj.jwpe.2025.108369&partnerID=40&md5=5e86bebfd3fc0549844c3b4bc60f5057},
	affiliations = {National Institute of Technology Silchar, Department of Mechanical Engineering, Silchar, AS, India; Metharath University, Bangkok, Thailand; Vel Tech Rangarajan Dr.Sagunthala R&D Institute of Science and Technology, Chennai, TN, India},
	abstract = {Wastewater collection and treatment plays a vital role in achieving sustainable development. This study presents an efficient single-step treatment of municipal wastewater using a solar still integrated with spherical cement balls and iron chips as thermal storage materials. Four configurations are evaluated: a conventional solar still (CSS) and three modified designs-MSS-P (spherical cemented balls), MSS-Q (iron chips), and MSS-R (combination of both). Experimental investigations are performed under the climatic conditions of Silchar city, India (24.758°N, 92.792°E) to analyze and compare distillate output, energy and exergy efficiencies, cost performance, environmental effect, and water quality. The MSS-R demonstrates the highest distillate yield of 4.2 L/m<sup>2</sup>/day, achieving a 49.7 % improvement over CSS. Energy efficiency of MSS-P, MSS-Q, and MSS-R is recorded as 35.5 %, 32.8 % and 43.5 %, while exergy efficiencies are 2.64 %, 2.36 %, and 3.72 %, respectively. MSS-R also showed the lowest cost per liter at $0.0165/L, with a 25.3 % reduction compared to CSS. The payback time for CSS and MSS-R are 224 and 158 days, respectively. Environmental analysis revealed MSS-R reduced net CO₂ emissions by 87.6 % compared to CSS, contributing significantly to sustainability. The corresponding carbon credit earnings for CSS, MSS-P, MSS-Q, and MSS-R are $94.3, $146.3, $129.1, and $177, respectively. Water quality analysis confirmed WHO and BIS compliance, with TSS and TDS reduced by 95.3 % and 95.4 %, enhancing clarity. COD and BOD are lowered by 96.04 % and 97.5 %, indicating effective removal of organic pollutants. This study confirms that energy storage materials enhance solar still performance and support sustainable, low-cost wastewater treatment. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
