	abstract = {The current study underscores the necessity of ongoing research to develop sustainable methods for water purification. Presently, the distilled water production industry is focused on purification of saline or tap water, while in this research work, reverse osmosis (RO) waste water is used as input for purification. A stepped solar still (SSS) loaded with nanoparticle-mixed beeswax (SSS-NB), coupled with a simple collector (SSS-NB-SC) and a modified collector (SSS-NB-MC), is tested at 25 mL/min of RO waste water to obtain fresh water. Among the tested systems, SSS-NB-MC is found to be the most economical, thermally stable, and eco-friendly. The SSS-NB-MC produced maximum distillate output of 4538.8 g. The average convective heat transfer coefficient (h<inf>c-avg</inf>) for the SSS-NB-MC is the maximum, being 25.65%, 41.10%, and 49.83% greater than those of the SSS-NB-SC, SSS-NB, and SSS, respectively. This system also led other systems with the highest values of carbon credits earned (1043.2), CO<inf>2</inf> mitigation (56.85 tons), productive cost ($0.6356), thermal efficiency (54.32%), and exergy efficiency (3.82%). The study concludes that the SSS-NB-MC could be an affordable and environmentally friendly solution for the purification of RO waste water, potentially aiding water purification industry in achieving the sustainability goal. © 2025 Taylor & Francis Group, LLC.},
