	abstract = {Designing and evaluating cogeneration systems presents a promising strategy for addressing energy, economic, and environmental challenges. In this context, combined heat and power (CHP) systems powered by biogas and digested sludge, by-products of anaerobic digestion (AD), have been gaining prominence in wastewater treatment plants (WWTP). This study compiles research on technologies and factors influencing the recovery of these by-products in integrated WWTP-AD-CHP systems. The feasibility of these systems is assessed from thermodynamic, exergoeconomic, exergoenvironmental, economic, and environmental perspectives. Exergetic efficiency and economic viability can be enhanced through operational optimizations and system component improvements. The implementation of additional cycles, such as Organic Rankine, Brayton, and Stirling, as well as integration with CO<inf>2</inf> capture and reuse technologies, show potential to reduce environmental impacts and increase the energy self-sufficiency of WWTPs. Exergoeconomic analysis has been widely used to evaluate the specific exergy costing, while exergoenvironmental analysis identifies the components with the highest environmental impact. The multidimensional analysis provides a comprehensive diagnosis of the sustainability of these systems, supporting decision-making in the planning and implementation of resource recovery systems in WWTPs. © 2025 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group.},
