	abstract = {Exergy is the maximum amount of energy in a system available for conversion to useful work, that which can be used. While water resource recovery facilities (WRRFs) are good at exploiting latent chemical and even kinetic energy, the thermal energy is largely overlooked. Yet the potential thermal capacity of wastewater is 80% of its total value. What if it could be leveraged to make our towns and cities more sustainable? More than 500 facilities/communities worldwide have done so, demonstrating the potential of sewage thermal energy use (STEU). This report explains the technology involved, presents approaches from North American case studies, addresses obstacles, and provides tools and tips for getting started. It also provides a primer on the physics and heat pump technology. It is based on the 2017 WE&RF ENER10c13 research project, State of the Science and Issues Related to Heat Recovery from Wastewater. © © 2017 Water Environment Federation.},
