	abstract = {The aim of this research is to show how biomethanisation of biogas by primary and secondary treatment of activated sludge from a wastewater treatment plant (WWTP) can be used as an alternative to fossil fuels. Biogas biomethanisation has competitive advantages and provides new opportunities for the use of this fuel. This will allow EU countries to address some important goals in their energy plans: to reduce the organic matter deposited in landfills, to reduce CO<inf>2</inf> emissions, and to find viable solutions to minimize the environmental impact of sewage sludge (SS). This study analyses the biogas combustion and energy recovery processes from a thermodynamic, thermoeconomic and exergetic point of view. The results show that, in the process, the boiler is the main source of irreversibility and exergy destruction. Moreover, the energy and exergy economic value of exhaust gases from the combustion chamber are significant and worth exploiting. For this reason, the present study explores the applicability and suitability of integrating a Stirling engine in such a process. The study reveals that it is possible to create a small micro-cogeneration system, which leads to sustainable waste management and energy savings in the treatment plant itself. © 2017 Nova Science Publishers, Inc.},
