	year = {2016},
	pages = {},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85084245008&partnerID=40&md5=4c9ba030336c49e01fa25195b59d1cd3},
	affiliations = {IMT Atlantique, Nantes, Pays-de-la-Loire, France; Veolia Research and Innovation, Limay, France; Politecnico di Torino, Turin, TO, Italy},
	abstract = {Integration of industrial waste heat into district heating networks (DHN) is an approach for substituting resource consumption through the use of low-temperature streams. Many studies are available, where technology and system comparisons are made, highlighting the usefulness of the approach. Since many studies do not use geometry-based DHN networks, they do not capture the possible gains and impacts in transient system condition. In this work, this issue is overcome through industrial waste heat integration into DHN using a thermo-fluid dynamic model of the DHN in combination with a dynamic heat exchanger model for transient consumer demand. The objective is to study the effect of low-temperature heat integration and possible energy service to the system by using measured data of subnetwork consumers and power plants of the DHN. The evaluation is carried out for a specific time-frame (start-up phase), which shows the impact of the integration for peak-load demand during the morning hours. The approach is applied to the largest DHN system in Torino/Italy using a waste-water treatment plant (WWTP) as the prosumer. Results show, that the integration of low-temperature waste streams results in a lower network temperature for various consumers and therefore a higher mass flow rate in the network to ensure full energy supply. Furthermore, 2<sup>nd</sup>-law efficiency was calculated to estimate the gains of the integration, where a total exergy efficiency increase of about 13 % was found. © 2016 University of Ljubljana.},
